data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow + ResetAbort

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource with built-in timeout
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout — throws on cancellation
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` supports cancellation (preferred)

Pass the token through so the work **actually stops**:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | The first overload (`Func<T>`) returns to the caller on timeout, but the work keeps running on the thread pool. This matches `Thread.Abort`'s *intent* but not its *behavior*. Only the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload cooperatively stops work. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** | It holds timers internally. The `using` statement handles this. The original code had no equivalent leak risk. |
| **`OperationCanceledException` vs `TimeoutException`** | Callers that caught `TimeoutException` still work. But if you let `OperationCanceledException` leak, callers won't recognize it — the `when` guard prevents this. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` had no cleanup logic here** | The original catch swallowed the abort silently. If your real code had cleanup in that block, move it to a `finally` or `CancellationToken.Register` callback. |
| **Blocking I/O won't respond to the token** | If `work` calls `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc., those ignore cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads that accept a token. |

### What was removed and why

| Removed | Replacement | Reason |
|---------|-------------|--------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (via timeout) | `SYSLIB0006` / `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No abort to reset; check `token.IsCancellationRequested` if you need to decide whether to continue |
| `new Thread(...)` + `.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; `Task` integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Token-aware waiting; `.NET 6+` API |
